For GaAs growth by D-HVPE, there are several factors that affect the growth rate in the mass-transport-limited HVPE growth parameter space. The first is the efficiency of the GaCl conversion reaction from HCl and Ga. This is governed in large part by the temperature in the source region, 800 °C in our case, but also by the residence time of the HCl in the Ga boat if the kinetics of the HCl to GaCl conversion reaction are not sufficiently fast. The HCl residence time in the Ga source boat is defined predominantly by the flow of H2 carrier gas that pushes the HCl through the boat, QH2Ga\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
